pullRequest.body:
[Leaff](https://github.com/alexjbest/leaff) is an experimental lean-diff tool, this PR is to experiment with adding it as a CI step.

---

I'm not sure yet if it is best to have this always run or only run on request (like bench).
If it is always run should it post a comment or simply leave its output it the actions log (maybe as a summary object)


the current iteration runs and updates a sticky comment with the latest result

nodes.body:
https://github.com/alexjbest/leaff reports
```diff
No differences found.
```

<!-- Sticky Pull Request Comment -->

I've authored about a dozen renaming or file splitting PRs recently. Personally, it would perfectly suffice to be able to trigger `leaff` with a comment. (I'm not sure if a `leaff` comment everywhere would lead to fatigue.)
Additionally, if `leaff` is opt-in, you could roll this out earlier - it doesn't have to be perfect. I'd rather have this now, as an alpha version, rather than waiting for a month for the perfect tool to arrive.

For small PRs or those only adding a few lemmas here and there, I don't think this output provides too much value. For large PRs (e.g. splitting files, moving declarations or renaming lemmas), having this tool to check would be extremely helpful --- both as an author and reviewer

Hi @grunweg thanks for the very helpful thoughts. My current plan is to improve Leaff a bit more to handle imports and things like move+rename as a single step better (and maybe attributes / envextensions) and then open a discussion on the Zulip. I think that the discussion may well be influenced by what the output of the tool looks like (if it is unnecessarily verbose that would be less desirable to always run). I'd like to get this done in the next couple of weeks.

If one wants to simply see the output of Leaff on a PR today, for now the easiest way is to make a new branch from the one you are working on (`git checkout my-working-branch; git checkout -b my-wrking-branch-with-leaff`), merge this branch into it (`git merge alexjbest/leaff`) and then push that so that CI will then run on it (somewhat quickly if there are oleans already) and the output will show up in the checks summary page (e.g. https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/6937276526?pr=8479)
Thanks for the quick response. Your plan makes sense to me; with the detailed instructions, I can bear the wait. :-)
What do we need to get it merged?

Well you could merge it as is, but I'm still making changes to leaff right now. It does use the current master so it would update in time. I'd say maybe if we wait a week I should be able to make sure leaff itself is a little more stable / well tested first.
Let me delegate it then. Please merge it whenever you feel that `leaff` is good enough.
bors d+

:v: alexjbest can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).
Thanks @urkud ! Will try and get it finished this week
Removing `delegated` so this doesn't clutter the queueboard.
